Public procurement of works and prevention of corruption
Joint report by the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (Sao) and the Federal Court of Auditors of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) on their parallel audits
Introduction and overview
The award of services by contracting authorities is of great importance both for the State and for the economy.
The role of the State is to use public funds as economically and economically as possible and to ensure fair and regulated competition.
In the European Union (EU), the award of services by contracting authorities is an important element in the creation of a single economic area.
In order to ensure largely unrestricted competition also across borders, contracting authorities must comply with EU requirements for their awards above certain thresholds.
To this end, EU Member States must transpose and apply EU public procurement law into national law.
This has already happened in both the Czech Republic and Germany.
Below the EU thresholds, it remains for each country to regulate public procurement itself.
The award of benefits is also an area at risk of corruption.
Therefore, because of the generally high potential for damage, contracting authorities should take appropriate measures to prevent and prevent corruption and inadmissible benefits when awarding their contracts.
In January 2011, the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (Sao) and the Federal Court of Auditors of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) agreed to carry out parallel audits both on the EU-wide award of construction services and on the prevention of corruption.
The audit focused on the application of EU public procurement law, each transposed into national legislation, and the prevention of corruption in the award of civil works in civil engineering, road construction and transport infrastructure.
Spending below the EU thresholds has also been included in the considerations with a view to preventing corruption.
The audit findings of both Courts are summarised in this Joint Report.
The report should also address international bodies such as the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI).
Audit areas and audited bodies The assessments of the Federal Court of Auditors on the listed topics are mainly based on cross-sectional audits carried out in 2011 / 2012 by the construction administrations for road and civil engineering. the federal government is responsible in Germany.
He examined, for example, the construction of motorways and major construction projects.
In addition, the Bundesrechnungshof used results from previous investigations.
The Chief Inspectorate of the Czech Republic based its evaluations on audit findings from 2008 to 2011, including road construction, railway construction, water construction, civil engineering (hospitals, cultural buildings, university buildings, etc.). as well as other construction areas in the Czech Republic.
In Germany, the federal public procurement is carried out predominantly by the construction administrations of the federal states.
In the Czech Republic, the State Building Administration is centrally responsible for the procurement of transport infrastructure.
In the construction sector, the allocations are implemented in a decentralised way by the bodies using the public budget.
In both countries, freelancers are also involved in sub-contracting procedures.
Differences in public procurement law and market structure for construction services in both countries should be taken into account when comparing the evaluations.
Structure of procurement law in both countries
In Germany, EU-wide procurement procedures are laid down in laws and regulations.
Procurement procedures restricted to national areas are governed by budgetary law and the administrative provisions on which they are based.
For both EU-wide and national public procurement, many complementary individual schemes are provided for by internal administrative provisions;
For example, the so-called "procurement manuals" of the federal government, which supplement or clarify the legal provisions in accordance with the case law on public procurement.
In the Czech Republic, the procurement procedure is governed exclusively by the public procurement law and other legal provisions applicable both above and below the EU thresholds.
Public procurement law was substantially revised in 2012.
The new regime increased transparency in the handling of public funds, allowed greater competition and limited the possibility of corruption in the procurement process.
Guiding principles of procurement law in both countries
In both countries, EU-wide procurement is subject in particular to the open procedure, the non-open procedure and the negotiated procedure.
In Germany, measures below the EU threshold should be subject to national contract types (public tendering, restricted tendering, free procurement) which, however, are broadly equivalent to those mentioned throughout the EU.
Public procurement law in Germany is characterised by the principle of "open procedure" (for EU-wide public procurement) and "public procurement" (for national public procurement).
In the case of an open procedure and in the case of a public tender, any interested company may submit an offer.
Another key feature of German public procurement law is the promotion of small and medium-sized enterprises.
The main purpose of this is to divide an overall construction measure into technical and partial buildings.
The individual award of these lots aims to enable as many companies as possible to participate in the competition.
Both of the above-mentioned features of German public procurement law are proven instruments for achieving economic results.
In Germany, there are over 330,000 construction companies with 1.9 million employees.
In the Czech Republic, EU-wide procurement procedures should also apply to construction projects below the EU threshold.
One exception is the simplified procedure where a less stringent procedure may be applied below the thresholds and under certain conditions.
The Czech public procurement law contains provisions in accordance with EU law whereby contracts are to be concluded when competition is ensured and a favourable price is achieved.
The current legislation in the Czech Republic allows contracting authorities to choose between the open and the non-open procedure.
There are over 85,000 construction companies in the Czech Republic, some 1,900 of which have 20 or more employees.
