Summary of the results of the parallel tests
The Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (Sao) and the Federal Court of Auditors of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) have carried out parallel checks in their countries on the EU-wide award of construction services and the prevention of corruption.
In this context, the working groups of both Courts compared the relevant legal bases and administrative requirements in the Czech Republic and Germany, as well as the results of their parallel audits, which they carried out in particular in the fields of construction and road construction.
They noted in essence:
The EU directives on the award of works by contracting authorities have been transposed into national law in both the Czech Republic and Germany (points 1 and 3.1).
In addition to EU standards, anti-corruption is also affected by the procurement arrangements of both countries, some of which differ in their priorities and details (point 3.2).
In both countries, an essential requirement for the award documents is that they must contain all the information needed to make an appropriate offer.
The performance descriptions shall be neutral and shall not be subject to restrictive competition rules.
In Germany, the award documents have largely complied with these requirements.
In the Czech Republic, it remains a problem to adequately determine the subject-matter of the contract.
In Germany, construction services must be divided as loosely as possible in order to promote competition.
According to the BRH, this requirement has been largely implemented in Germany.
