Fundamentals of EU public procurement law and anti-corruption
EU public procurement law
In order to ensure unrestricted competition within the European Union in the free movement of services and goods, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union have adopted, inter alia, the Directive on coordination of awards and the Directive on remedies, which Member States have adopted in national law8. to be implemented.
The general principles governing the award of contracts in the European Union are, in particular, the prohibition of competition, the principle of equal treatment or the prohibition of discrimination and the prohibition of transparency.
To achieve these objectives, the procurement coordination directive contains specific rules for construction works to be awarded throughout the EU.
To achieve this, their estimated contract amounts must reach or exceed €5,000,000 at present.
The arrangements concern in particular the content of the contract documents, the publication of certain information before, during and after the award, the observance of deadlines, including for the receipt of tenders, the documentation of the contract award procedure, the requirements relating to the qualification of the contract. candidates can be placed and the Remedies Directive forms the basis for the legal protection of candidates and tenderers.
In the event of possible infringements of public procurement law, the undertakings concerned may have the decisions of the contracting authorities reviewed in review proceedings.
Both the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have transposed the European Union directives into national law.
Prevention of corruption
The importance of preventing corruption
In both countries there is no legal definition of the concept of corruption.
In general, corruption means the abuse of confidence to the private advantage,
It is initiated by the beneficiaries of these decisions.
Corruption can hinder competition and cause significant economic damage.
It is estimated that the worldwide cost of corruption is 5% of world economic output.
For the European Union, the level of these costs is estimated at 1%.
In the case of contracting authorities, restrictive agreements or unfair practices may undermine confidence in the integrity and functioning of the administration.
Preventing corruption is therefore one of the fundamental tasks of public purchasers.
They will have to review the structure and structure of their administrations in areas particularly vulnerable to corruption in order to provide appropriate safeguards against corruption.
Preventive measures and effective controls can significantly reduce the vulnerability of decision-making to corruptive abuse.
The award of public works services is considered to be a particularly vulnerable area of work.
Anti-corruption measures
In Germany, corruption – in particular bribery and bribery, as well as advantage-taking and authorisation – is prosecuted under criminal and labour law.
In order to prevent corruption, the Federal Government has adopted a directive and recommendations on prevention of corruption12 in the Federal Administration. in addition to risk analysis, the following principles should be taken into account for the awarding sector in particular: priority of public tenders and open procedures, multi-eyed principle and transparency, fundamental separation of planning, award and settlement, accurate and complete documentation of procurement procedures.
In addition, other anti-corruption requirements have been included in public procurement rules.
For example, in 2011, the competent Federal Ministry for Distance Road Contracts introduced an electronically-supported control system,
Data on contracts, such as estimated costs and contract amounts, as well as information on the freelance workers involved are collected across the board and evaluated for fragility.
Corruption is also prosecuted under criminal and labour law in the Czech Republic.
The legal provisions on transparency and equal treatment of tenderers, as well as the prohibition of any discrimination, are the main foundations for preventing corruption.
For public procurement, the Czech government has identified anti-corruption measures in a strategy paper on anti-corruption for 2011-2012 and updated them for 2013-2014.
Some of the measures recommended have already been transposed into national public procurement law and corresponding administrative provisions14.
The new legislation essentially contains the following rules: reduction of thresholds for smaller contracts, obligation for the contracting authority to publish the contracts beforehand, including the reasons for the tender, prohibition of limiting the number of tenderers in non-open procedures and thus abolition of the possibility of selecting bidders through lot procedures, introduction of the obligation to publish the contract documents and all annexes, introduction of the obligation to publish the actual price and the list of subcontractors. "
Results of each stage of the procurement procedure
Contract documents
Procurement documents The procurement documents must contain all the information needed by the tenderers for an appropriate preparation of the tender.
In particular, the award documents must allow for an accurate calculation.
They shall not be allowed to transfer to the tenderers any risks which they cannot calculate.
The contract documents shall consist in particular of the service description and the contractual terms and conditions.
They shall also include the criteria for proof of the qualification (suitability) of the tenderers and the criteria relevant to the selection of the most economical offer.
Requirements of EU law and prevention of corruption
The requirements of EU law on procurement documents are specifically addressed to the technical specifications.
They should be equally accessible to all tenderers and should limit competition as little as possible.
In principle, the service description must be product-neutral.
For this reason, information on products or manufacturers as part of the description of performance is only allowed under strict conditions.
Avoiding anti-competitive requirements in the tendering documents is also a fundamental principle of preventing corruption.
In addition, unclear or incorrect information in the procurement documents should be avoided as they provide room for speculation when preparing the tenders and for manipulation when evaluating them.
Rules of German and Czech public procurement law
Similar or similar arrangements In both countries, EU rules on technical specifications are transposed into national law.
The services must in principle be tendered on a product-neutral basis without a specification of the manufacturer.
In the service descriptions, each service must normally be subdivided into service units with the respective quantities.
Prices must be agreed on the basis of service units (e.g. euro per m 2 or per piece).
Only in exceptional cases can services be defined by means of functional objectives.
In any event, the service descriptions must be complete and clear.
They must contain accurate quantities and must not include services which do not determine whether they are needed.
Remuneration by flat rate or time should be avoided as far as possible.
The purpose of these provisions is to prevent speculation and manipulation based on indeterminate specifications in the award documents.
The service descriptions must enable tenderers to prepare their offers safely and without extensive preparatory work.
The tender should not be published until the contract documents have been completed.
Different arrangements
There is no obligation to tender for construction services in lots in the Czech Republic.
Where possible according to the type of service to be charged, public contracting entities may divide construction services into several lots.
In Germany, construction works must in principle be divided into lots, separately by quantity (portions) and / or by type or subject area (s).
The aim is to enable SMEs to participate in competition, to increase the number of potential suppliers and to make price agreements more difficult.
This type of award is usually considered to be the most economical.
Evaluation criteria must be indicated in the procurement documents in the Czech Republic for both EU-wide and national procedures.
The aim is to ensure that candidates are fully and conclusively aware of the criteria under which their offers are to be assessed.
In Germany, valuation criteria are required in EU-wide notices, but at the latest in the award documents, only for EU-wide procurement procedures.
In the case of national procurement procedures, the evaluation criteria shall only be set out in an internal procurement notice.
Contract documents drawn up by contracted professionals may not contain any references to these offices or planners or experts involved in the construction and some road construction administrations in Germany.
The aim is to prevent individual undertakings from obtaining additional information or other undue competitive advantages without the knowledge of the contracting authority concerning their contact with those professionals.
This is also the reason why freelance contracting documents may not be sent or interpreted for inspection.
The contact point for businesses is the contracting authority alone.
There is currently no provision for this in the Czech Republic.
Additional or modified services which prove necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (supplements) almost always apply to large construction projects.
In both countries, the legal provisions allow, to a certain extent, the award of contracts to the undertaking already commissioned without the need to conduct a public procurement procedure.
According to EU and German provisions, the remuneration of supplementary services must not exceed half of the principal contract.
Moreover, the additional services must not be separated from the main contract without significant disadvantages or must be absolutely necessary.
In the Czech Republic, a closer 20% threshold applies to awards without public notice.
However, this may increase the risk of delayed completion of the construction project or the need to involve an additional contractor in the construction work already underway.
If supplementary services are also transferred to the undertaking already appointed, the German rules do not allow an arbitrary price increase for these services by the contractor in principle.
In determining the remuneration for the additional services, the agreed prices and the basis for determining the prices of the contract already awarded should be taken into account.
In addition to supplementary services, the scope of services may also be reduced.
In the Czech Republic, minority quantities cannot be charged with additional supplementary benefits.
Main results of the audit
BHR
Technical specifications and product-neutral tendering
In individual cases, the service descriptions contained references to national technical approvals or standards which had already been replaced by European-wide standards.
Some performance descriptions also included product-related specifications – such as graphite protection, joint tapes or noise protection plates – without this being necessary.
In some cases, performance requirements were described so precisely that only one product was eligible.
Lists of performance broken down by partial performance
The BRH has not found any infringement of the obligation to tender services in principle in a list of services broken down by partial services in any of the procedures examined.
Completeness of service descriptions
In the vast majority of cases, the contract documents were completed before the commencement of tenders.
For some procedures, the tender documents had to be corrected during the tender phase, as some positions or deadlines had changed.
In isolation, the performance lists contained positions where they were not determined whether they were needed.
Almost half of the performance index for demolition consisted of such demand positions.
Loose and valuation criteria
Many contracts lacked the required justification for the failure to divide the services largely advertised by professionals into poles.
There were no objections to the criteria to be used in the evaluation of the tenders.
References to freelance workers
A small part of the service descriptions contained references to the professionals involved.
Their names were partly on the cover sheets or in attached plans or opinions.
In one case, the contracting authority even explicitly asked the candidates to contact the architect "on tender issues."
In particular in the construction sector, the contracting authorities mainly attributed the reported complaints to the failure of the freelance workers responsible for drawing up the service descriptions.
The building services pointed to the lack of capacity to adequately control the performance descriptions.
