Summary findings
The basic rules on procurement documents are broadly consistent in both countries and take into account EU requirements.
They serve both comprehensive and fair competition and the prevention of corruption.
For example, the requirement of adequate definition of the service descriptions should enable tenderers to calculate and prepare their offers in an appropriate manner;
Protect the contracting authority against additional services to be subsequently agreed and also reduce speculation space.
The common basic requirements on award documents are supplemented in Germany by regulations aimed at further reducing restrictions on competition and the possibility of manipulation.
In the Czech Republic, there are no such benchmarks, but transparency is enhanced by the publication of valuation criteria for non-EU procurement procedures.
The performance description requirements have been largely complied with in both countries.
In some cases, however, deviations had to be criticised, which could also have led to restrictions on competition.
The lot-making requirement in Germany encourages competition and leads to economic results.
In the Czech Republic, according to audit findings of the Sao, the award of substantial services without lots or with very large lots may result in restrictions on the field of operators to a few large companies.
The extensive reference requirements imposed in the Czech Republic in road construction have led to public contracts being awarded only to a narrow range of suppliers and not allowing smaller and medium-sized enterprises to participate in competition.
A limited number of competitors often lead to higher prices and increase the risk of price or other agreements.
As regards the award and remuneration of additional or modified services, regulatory approaches differ from one country to another.
Under EU and German rules, supplementary services with a value of up to half of the principal contract may be awarded without public procurement under certain conditions.
The Czech Republic has a closer 20% threshold up to which additional services can be awarded to the original contractor in the negotiated procedure without notification.
