Defining the type of award and taking into account the EU threshold
By specifying the type of award, the contracting authority shall determine the number of companies participating in the competition.
It may leave the range of potential candidates and tenderers to a large extent unrestricted, for example by selecting an open procedure, or by imposing non-public award procedures.
For construction projects where a threshold set by the EU is reached or exceeded, pan-European procurement procedures shall apply.
Requirements of EU law and prevention of corruption
In choosing the type of award, the contracting authority shall take into account, in particular, the requirements of European law relating to competition and transparency.
If the estimated total contract value of a project's construction works is equal to or above the current EU threshold of €5,000,000, construction works must in principle be awarded throughout Europe using open or non-open procedures.
In exceptional cases, negotiation procedures or competitive dialogue are also possible.
The contracting authority may deviate to a limited extent from the principle of pan-European award of construction projects which reach or exceed the EU threshold and may award construction services in national contracts, provided that the estimated contract each lot is less than €1,000,000 and the sum of these lots does not exceed 20% of the estimated total value of all works contracts.
A single construction project should not be divided into individual measures without a necessary reason or deliberately estimated at too low costs in order to avoid the obligation to award construction services in principle throughout Europe.
As restrictions on competition significantly increase the risk of manipulation, the choice of award is of great importance in the prevention of corruption.
The detailed justification of the choice of award procedure and the verification of the application of the EU public procurement rules are important elements of the documentation of the award procedure.
Rules of German and Czech public procurement law
Same or similar arrangements
Both countries have fully transposed EU rules on procurement procedures and thresholds into national law.
Different arrangements
The Czech Republic has also transferred the principle of equal treatment between open and non-open procedures contained in the EUR Directive to its works contracts, which are not subject to EU standards.
There is a freedom of choice between the open and the non-open procedure without the need to mention or justify the decision, while other procedures are only possible under certain legally defined conditions.
In Germany, however, the open procedure or – in the case of national contracts – the public tender is in principle a priority, as determined by budgetary and public procurement law as well as by the anti-corruption directives.
Other types of awards, such as the non-open procedure or the restricted tender procedure, are only possible in exceptional cases which are finally regulated by public procurement law.
The existence of an exception shall be understandably justified and documented.
The principle of "open procedure" or "public tender" is designed to ensure as unrestricted competition as possible, exclude possibilities of manipulation by setting certain tenderers and possible price agreements between tenderers. difficulties.
The principle of public tendering in Germany is a central element in the prevention of corruption.
The correct estimate of the expected value of the contract is an essential basis for choosing the right type of contract.
Building services in Germany can use planning and cost databases from public administrations and other organisations to determine the expected costs of public building.
These databases are based on evaluations of completed construction projects, including cost indicators for building categories, utility units, components or individual construction services.
On the basis of such cost indicators, the estimated contract value of a planned project or a construction performance to be awarded can be determined.
Corresponding cost databases for road construction only have some construction administrations in Germany.
Nevertheless, a nationwide introduction is foreseen for all road construction administrations.
Contracting entities in the Czech Republic cannot use central databases or average price investigations of comparable construction measures to determine the expected costs of construction works.
In the majority of cases, cost investigations are based on estimates of the funding body or are based on the amount of funds made available to the building service.
Measures to standardise cost investigations are still in the process of being implemented.
Within the framework of the anti-corruption plan for 2011-2012, the competent ministries were mandated to establish a database on standardised building materials and materials.
