Main results of the BRH
Choice of award procedure
The audited contracting entities largely wrote out the construction services in the open procedure or in the public tender procedure and thus followed the budgetary and public procurement rules.
In 2011, 59.5% of the federal construction services were publicly procured in civil engineering and open procedures.
In road construction, this figure was 94.8%.
In the choice of non-public tenderers, some detailed reasons were lacking as to why contracting entities had to deviate from the principle of open procedure or public tender.
In a cross-sectoral investigation, the BRH found, on the basis of more than 16,000 procurement procedures, that non-public tenderers have significant competitive disadvantages compared to open procedures and public tenders and that manipulation and corruption increase risk.
In construction, more than twice as many tenders were submitted in public tenders as in restricted tenders and almost three times as many offers were submitted in the case of freelance contracts.
The study also showed that on average tender prices for restricted tenders and contracts for freelancers were 6% and 10% higher than for public tenders.
Parallel studies carried out by the Federal Ministry of Buildings and a State Court of Auditors confirmed the differences in economic efficiency between public and non-public contracts.
As a result of its studies on economic efficiency, the Federal Ministry of Buildings even experienced twice as many differences between public and non-public procurement procedures.
