Selection of candidates for non-public awards
In contrast to public procurement procedures, non-public procurement procedures do not allow any undertaking interested in the performance of the services to be awarded to participate in competition.
In the case of non-public procurement procedures, the contracting authority shall select in advance which undertakings are to be invited to submit tenders.
Requirements of EU law and anti-corruption The EU rules allow a limitation of the number of candidates in non-public procurement procedures across the EU.
However, in the case of non-open procedures, at least five companies must be invited to submit tenders.
At least three companies shall be invited to negotiate with a contract notice.
In any event, the number of candidates invited must be sufficient to ensure genuine competition.
The selection criteria must be objective, must not lead to discrimination and must be announced beforehand.
The selection of companies to be requested is an operation within the procurement procedure that is highly vulnerable to manipulations, e.g. by giving unilateral preference to certain companies.
Moreover, restricting competition to few companies also favours possible agreements between candidates.
In both cases, the outcome of the contract may be significantly affected at the expense of the contracting authority.
The contracting authorities must therefore take special measures against possible manipulations, carry out adequate controls and, in particular, ensure the transparency and traceability of this process.
Rules of German and Czech public procurement law
Same or similar arrangements
The arrangements for selecting candidates are similar in both countries.
In addition to EU standards, contracting entities should switch as often as possible between the companies to be called upon when selecting candidates.
Competition must not be restricted to companies established in certain regions.
The contracting authorities shall state the reasons for the selection of candidates and document the selection procedure in their procurement documents.
Different arrangements
In Germany at least three tenders should be restricted and in principle several suitable tenderers should be invited to tender.
The new Czech legislation does not allow the number of tenderers to be restricted in non-open procedures and negotiated procedures, with the exception of two specific areas.
In Germany, the choice of companies must respect the "multi-eye" principle.
For example, where an employee has proposed a number of undertakings for a non-public award procedure, the management level of the building service or a contracting authority must normally change this proposal by exempting a proposed undertaking, for example: complement the undertaking and / or a new undertaking.
The aim is to prevent a single person from finally determining the circle of the undertakings to be competing.
Otherwise, this could allow far-reaching agreements among stakeholders in the event of manipulative intentions.
The list of companies to be requested should be treated confidentially, including with regard to professionals, and should not be made publicly available.
