Due to the high risk of manipulation in the selection of candidates in non-public procurement procedures, both countries have taken special measures to prevent undue restrictions of competition.
By means of the multi-eyed principle, the confidentiality of the lists of bidders and the sole power of the contracting authorities to propose the companies to be invited, the German rules limit such abuses.
In particular, the newly introduced requirement for the largely unlimited number of bidders in non-public procedures may prevent possible manipulative restrictions.
