Offering phase
With the publication of the tender or the invitation to tender, the offering phase begins, during which companies can prepare tenders on the basis of the contract documents sent to them.
Applicants may submit their offers until the expiry of the deadline set by the contracting authority.
Requirements of EU law and prevention of corruption
There are no separate EU rules for this stage of the award procedure.
Contracting entities must respect national rules to counteract the possibilities of manipulation existing during the tender phase.
These are mainly organisational requirements and controls.
Rules of German and Czech public procurement law
Same or similar arrangements
The contract documents on the basis of which companies are to prepare their tenders shall in principle be sent only by the contracting authority.
Freelancers participating in the award procedure shall not be allowed to carry out this task.
The contracting authority shall ensure that all candidates receive the same information during the tender phase.
In the event of uncertainty about the contract documents or other questions relating to the tendering procedure, only the contracting authority may provide information to the applicants.
Freelance workers who are responsible for drawing up the contract documents may not provide any information.
During the whole offering phase, contacts should be avoided between the contracted professionals and the candidates.
Professionals should not be allowed to become a turntable of the award procedure through which contacts can be established with anti-competitive consequences.
Tenders shall be submitted by post or directly transmitted in a closed envelope.
Electronically transmitted offers shall have a technical encryption.
Different arrangements
In Germany, the contracting authority may also commission the printing and dispatch of the contract documents to external service companies whose staff are required to keep the tenders confidential and to carry out the contractual obligations conscientiously.
The offers received must be marked with a receipt stamp in Germany and sent directly, without delay and without delay to an official responsible for the detention.
Such staff shall not be involved in the procurement process.
The offers received shall be kept closed until the opening date.
In the Czech Republic, the offers received are marked with a file number.
The contracting authority shall keep the tender data, including the order numbers and the preparation and receipt information, in a protocol.
The preservation of tenders in the Czech Republic is not further regulated.
