Examination and evaluation of tenders
Examination and evaluation of tenders The contracting authority shall examine and evaluate the tenders available at the opening date.
It is required to determine the tender for the award of the contract that best meets the requirements according to the specified award criteria.
Requirements of EU law and prevention of corruption
The EU's guidelines provide for a multi-stage procedure:
First, the suitability of the tenderers should be established.
Tenderers must be economically and financially efficient and have the necessary professional and technical expertise.
Participation in the procurement procedure should in principle be excluded from participation in the procurement procedure for companies which are legally convicted for, for example, bribery or fraud.
The tenders offered by the non-excluded tenderers shall be computerised, technically and economically examined and evaluated on the basis of the award criteria previously announced.
The contracting authority shall determine the most economically advantageous offer, and tenders with unusually low prices shall be specifically considered by the contracting authority.
The examination and evaluation of tenders is a particularly vulnerable phase of the award procedure.
For example, bidders may be unjustifiedly excluded or offers that do not meet the requirements may be left in competition.
The advantage or disadvantage of tenderers may inadmissibly affect the result of the evaluation and thus prevent the establishment of the most economically advantageous tender.
The contracting authority should therefore make special arrangements to ensure that the persons entrusted with the audit and evaluation meet the requirements of integrity and expertise.
It must also ensure the transparency and traceability of the procedure and the decisions taken.
Rules of German and Czech public procurement law
Same or similar arrangements
In line with EU requirements, offers in both countries should be examined and evaluated in multi-stage procedures.
The requirements for the qualifications to be submitted by the undertakings and the award criteria to be taken into account in the evaluation and their weighting shall be laid down in the notices or tender documents and shall not be amended during the procedure of the
After examining the suitability of the tender, the eligibility criteria may no longer be used in the evaluation of the tenders.
The evaluation should be limited to the award criteria.
The offers submitted must first be formally examined as soon as possible, whether they are complete and whether they contain, for example, suggestions that might indicate possible manipulation intentions.
Where bidders are excluded from further examination and evaluation of their bids, they shall be informed thereof without delay.
If the evaluation of the tenders results in an unreasonably low price, the tenderer must be given the opportunity to comment before possible exclusion of his tender.
The decisions taken in examining and evaluating the tenders shall be documented in a comprehensible manner.
Different arrangements
In Germany, the offers to be kept secret may only be made available to persons directly responsible for processing.
Only the contracting authority may carry out the review of the tenders and the calculation of the tenders.
It shall only employ staff who are not involved in the award decision or the implementation of the measure.
The performance of further audit and evaluation tasks is not clearly regulated.
Where freelance workers are entrusted with auditing and evaluation, they must keep the offers confidential.
They may only make proposals for decisions to be taken by the contracting authorities.
In the Czech Republic, procurement committees should be set up to examine and evaluate the tenders.
The Committees shall draw up evaluation reports with proposals for awarding contracts.
Ultimately, as in Germany, only contracting entities have to decide on contracts.
If evidence or declarations required for tendering in Germany are submitted incompletely, the contracting authority shall give the tenderers the opportunity to submit the missing documents within six days.
It is only when the documents are still not available after the deadline that the offer should be excluded from the valuation.
In the Czech Republic, it is at the discretion of the contracting authority whether it gives bidders the opportunity to complete missing evidence or statements.
If a tenderer fails to do so, it must be excluded.
In Germany, in addition to the total price, the unit prices (prices for partial services) of the offers should also be examined.
If the price structure of the offer indicates that prices for partial services are too low or too high, the tenderer shall be required to remedy these uncertainties.
If it does not succeed and if the contracting authority can provide evidence of a mixed calculation of prices, this offer shall be excluded.
The aim is to prevent tenderers from speculating on substantial quantity changes in partial services when calculating their offer, which can lead to significant cost increases in construction projects.
In the Czech Republic, the total price is assessed, but not the adequacy of the prices of partial services.
A mixed calculation cannot justify the exclusion of an offer.
A contract may not be awarded in Germany for offers with unreasonably high or low prices.
Where one or more offers are below the actual price calculation of the contracting authority or the sum offered by the other tenderers by 10% or more, the tenderers shall prove the correct calculation of their offers.
If they are not able to do so, the contracting authority may exclude the tenders concerned.
In the Czech Republic, the tendering procedure may be abolished after consideration of economic viability if only offers are available at unjustifiable low prices.
In contrast to German public procurement law, the award cannot be refused for offers with prices significantly higher than the calculation of the contracting authority.
Where there is a suspicion of restrictive behaviour in Germany, the contracting authority shall report without delay to the leading level of its technical supervision.
It must decide on the measures to be taken and whether to inform the antitrust authority or the public prosecutor.
For example, in the case of construction services above EUR 50 000, the supervisory authority must also agree when it is intended to award a contract free of charge, when it is not intended to award a contract at the lowest price or when the tender is to be abolished.
There are no such arrangements in the Czech Republic.
