For many of the projects audited, including higher education, road construction and the development of the railway network, contracting entities did not exclude tenderers from the procedure, although they did not meet the requirements set out in the tender documents, or on the other hand, a contracting authority could neither prove nor explain why it had excluded a tenderer who had complied with the requirements.
Valuation
When awarding construction services for a water treatment plant, the contracting authority failed to take into account the criteria for assessing and evaluating the tenders.
In the case of a construction project for the development of the railway network, the contracting authority determined the weighting of the evaluation criteria only at the beginning of the evaluation.
In the case of road conservation measures, a procedure misjudged the criterion of "shortening the construction phase."
This resulted in insufficient consideration being given to the shortening offered by second and third position bidders.
Documentation of tender selection
In three procurement procedures in the context of housing promotion, the contracting authority did not document what criteria it applied and on what basis it had selected the successful tenderer.
When building a motorway, the contracting authority selected companies for smaller orders up to €20,000 because of telephone surveys on prices and delivery conditions alone.
Examinations of this selection were not possible because the surveys were not documented.
Summary findings
The arrangements for examining and evaluating offers in both countries comply with the EU's requirements.
However, as regards the details of the procedure and the selection of the persons involved, the rules differ from one another.
In Germany, detailed requirements, in particular regarding the implementation of the multi-eye principle and the protection of offers, regulate the process more strongly than in the Czech Republic.
The same applies to the benchmarks on the basis of which the adequacy of the offered prices should be assessed.
In both countries, some of the procurement procedures examined had to conclude that substantial procedural steps in the examination and evaluation of tenders were not or were insufficiently documented.
However, without traceability and transparency of audit and evaluation decisions, possible manipulative interventions will be encouraged.
A particularly serious shortcoming was the handing over of all offers to third parties without the contracting authority having previously sufficiently scrutinised and documented the offers, thereby protecting them from possible manipulations in the subsequent procedure.
When contracting authorities perform tasks in assessing and evaluating offers by third parties, sufficient arrangements and an increased control burden are needed to counteract the increased risk of manipulation.
When assessing the adequacy of prices, the services audited in Germany did not always make full use of the set of instruments and did not adequately analyse the price structure of the offers.
In the Czech Republic, complaints were raised mainly concerning the aptitude test and the application of the evaluation criteria.
Conclusion of the award procedure
After examining and evaluating the tenders, the award procedure is concluded by awarding the contract or by abolishing the procedure.
Requirements of EU law and prevention of corruption
For EU-wide procurement procedures, all tenderers shall be informed in advance of the proposed award decision.
Companies have the possibility to review the intended award of information by electronic means or by fax within 10 days or within 15 days for other means of communication and, where appropriate, to initiate a review procedure.
A contract may not be concluded before the expiry of this information period.
