Where a bidder submits a request for review within the information period, the conclusion of a contract shall be possible only after the final decision has been taken in the review procedure.
Companies may also have the award decision reviewed by an independent court in the course of this review procedure.
The purpose of the review procedure is to ensure the legal protection of companies and to encourage the contracting authority to comply with the law of the contracting authority throughout the procurement procedure.
To this end, it must provide adequate documentation of the procedure.
Rules of German and Czech public procurement law
Same or similar arrangements
Both countries have implemented EU rules on information and verification procedures.
In both countries, the contracting authority must decide on the award of the contract.
It must not, however, deviate arbitrarily from the outcome of a proper examination and evaluation of the tenders.
The contracting authority shall award the contract within the announced deadline for awarding the contract,
Also because the tenderers are no longer bound by their offers after the expiry of the period.
In the case of open and non-open procedures or public and limited invitations to tender, the contracting authority shall in principle not deviate from the content of the tender when the contract is concluded.
The inferior tenderers shall be informed promptly of the award decision and of the reasons for not taking into account their tenders.
Procurement procedures may only be abolished under certain conditions, e.g. if the offer prices are excessive or if the offers do not comply with the requirements of the tender.
Different arrangements
In the Czech Republic, the obligation to provide information and waiting for 10 or 15 days before awarding the contract also applies to non-European construction services.
In Germany, these guidelines apply only to EU-wide public procurement.
In the case of the other procedures in Germany, the tenderers may not be informed of the award decision until they have been awarded the contract.
In the Czech Republic, a tendering procedure should be abolished if only one tender has been received or if only one tender could be assessed.
In Germany, the award must also be awarded in the case of a single value-added offer, provided that it complies with the terms of the tender and is economical.
Main results of the audit
BRH
There were few complaints when the procurement procedures were completed in relation to the contracts audited.
In some cases, EU-wide contracts were awarded to companies prior to the expiry of the information deadlines, which may lead to the ineffectiveness of the contract.
In addition, letters of formal notice, following open procedures, contained, in individual cases, contents which deviate from the content of the offer, such as changed deadlines.
In several cases, the contracting authorities did not comply with the award deadlines.
In an open procedure, a contracting authority therefore awarded the second most favourable tender since a company with a 50% favourable tender after the contract period was no longer willing to carry out the services at the originally offered price.
