In the case of a construction project in the higher education sector, the contracting authority deviated from the tenderer's offer in terms of content.
In the case of certain contracts, such as road maintenance, motorway construction and bypass, contracting entities concluded contracts after the expiry of the statutory period.
When awarding construction works for the renovation of former military sites, the contracting authority only forwarded the award notification to all tenderers after the legal deadline.
Summary findings
Both countries have implemented the EU benchmarks for completing the award procedure.
The legal protection of the disadvantaged candidates or tenderers increases the range of anti-corruption tools.
The scope of legal protection in Czech public procurement law is also extended to awards below EU thresholds.
In both countries, deadlines for the award of contracts have been exceeded.
This can lead to economic disadvantages and increase the risk of manipulation.
Building administrations should avoid the shortcomings identified when completing their procurement procedures in the future.
Documentation, reporting and reporting obligations
The procurement procedures shall be documented in each stage in terms of the relevant findings and the reasons for each decision.
In EU-wide procedures, the contracts awarded must be made public.
The contract data will also be collected in an EU statistics.
Requirements of EU law and anti-corruption Documentation of procurement procedures implements a fundamental requirement of the EU-wide transparency offer.
A careful and timely documentation only allows for traceability of procurement decisions.
It also serves in particular to effectively protect tenderers from contracts above the EU thresholds.
Proper documentation is also an essential element in preventing corruption, since the need to substantiate procurement decisions considerably provides room for manoeuvre.
The notification of a contract awarded under an EU-wide award procedure shall be sent by the contracting authority to the EU's Official Publications Office within 48 days.
The Office publishes the notices in the Official Journal of the EU and thus implements the transparency requirement.
The contracting authorities shall also collect the essential data of their procurement procedures and report to the Commission through the relevant national ministries.
On this basis, the Commission draws up an annual EU statistics to provide an overview of the development of the internal market in construction services.
Rules of German and Czech public procurement law
Same or similar arrangements
Both countries have fully transposed EU documentation and reporting requirements into national law.
The rules on documentation and reporting for EU statistics are largely identical in both countries.
Different arrangements
In the Czech Republic, the obligation to publish contracts awarded is not limited to EU-wide awards, but also covers other award procedures.
The notice period is reduced to 15 days.
In Germany, in addition to EU-wide awards, publication obligations apply only to limited invitations to tender and to freelance contracts with a value limit of EUR 25 000 or EUR 15 000, respectively, without VAT (so-called ex-post transparency).
Below these limits and in the case of public tenders, only the companies involved in the competition proceedings will be informed of the award of contracts.
