Summary evaluation and recommendations
The parallel audits of the Sao and the BRH focused on two priorities, which are essential in the Czech Republic and Germany for the award of works by public contracting authorities: the application of EU public procurement rules and the prevention of corruption.
The requirements of EU law will allow cross-border competition to create a European single market.
Anti-corruption measures are not only designed to prevent or at least reduce corruption, but also to avert economic damage and a possible loss of confidence in the integrity of the state.
The audit findings of the two Courts of Auditors on the application of the rules governing public procurement in both countries and the comparison of those rules indicate similarities and differences for both countries in the further development of their procurement law and its application. use may be helpful.
Application of EU public procurement rules
Both countries have transposed the EU's rules on the award of construction services into national law.
This provides an important common basis for the award of construction services in the Czech Republic and Germany, taking into account the essential requirements of competition, equal treatment of the parties and transparency of procurement procedures.
The construction administrations of both countries have partially very extensively supported these bids through further administrative provisions.
The Czech Republic has to a large extent also transposed the requirements for EU-wide construction services to its nationally regulated procurement procedures below the EU threshold.
However, the audits carried out by the Courts have shown that the construction administrations have not fully complied with the requirements of EU law in all areas.
The construction administration in Germany should further improve the quality of its procurement procedures in order to remedy the complaints identified when implementing EU requirements.
The checks carried out in the Czech Republic have identified in particular dangers which affect the cost-effectiveness of the contracts.
For example, incomplete service descriptions required additional services, which were often awarded in breach of legislation, and cost investigations were usually inadequate and excessive skills requirements were reduced. possible bidders and restricted competition, particularly in the case of transport buildings.
Prevention of corruption
The investigation did not aim to detect cases of corruption,
Also because the Courts of Auditors do not have the appropriate tools.
However, the Courts of Auditors may examine the extent to which the administrations of both countries have taken steps against corruption and manipulation in the award of construction works and how these rules are applied.
In the prevention of corruption, both countries have put different priorities.
In particular, the German rules provide for largely unrestricted competition and transparency and controls as key elements in the prevention of corruption.
The main objective of the Czech legislation is to increase the transparency of procedures.
BRH
In Germany, the general principles of prevention of corruption apply to the entire federal administration.
These principles are also implemented in the provisions on the award of construction works and are geared to their specific needs.
The corresponding arrangements set out in some cases very precisely how corruption prevention requirements should be taken into account when tendering procedures are conducted and when selecting the persons involved.
In particular, the fry considers that the primacy of the principle of open procedure or public tendering is an appropriate instrument to significantly reduce the risk of corruption in the award of construction services. the risk of manipulative interventions.
Risk analysis and adequate controls (in particular the multi-eyed principle), transparency and documentation of procurement procedures, as well as various organisational measures, are also effective measures to prevent corruption and manipulation.
The fry therefore does not see a need for any fundamental changes to the corresponding provisions of the administrations concerning the award of works.
In practice, anti-corruption arrangements are largely taken into account.
The shortcomings identified in sub-sectors have identified shortcomings in the implementation of some benchmarks.
Construction administrations should continue to train their staff on anti-corruption requirements and raise their awareness of this issue.
A substantial part of the complaints concerned tasks delegated by construction administrations to professionals.
However, without controls and adequate safeguards, the risk of abuse increases when delegating tasks.
Manipulation and corruption-threatening tasks should therefore only be entrusted to third parties if the administration can ensure a sufficient level of protection against inadmissible interventions.
