The Czech Republic has decided at government level to adopt a strategy against corruption in which public procurement is the main component.
The procurement law and its implementing provisions have been substantially amended.
Audits of the Sao were carried out during the implementation of this strategy.
The strategy adopted and the new legislative provisions should be effective improvement measures, as contracting entities are responsible for the cost-effectiveness of contracts, the calculation of expected prices, the adequacy of qualification requirements, the essential evaluation criteria. and must justify the nature of the evaluations and properly document and publish all these aspects.
Recommendations
The Sao and the BRH consider the implementation of EU standards in principle positive.
The broad acceptance in practice has confirmed that EU offers of competition, equal treatment and transparency are an appropriate basis for the award of construction services within the European Union.
The supranational model implemented in the European Union can also serve as a basis for similar projects to facilitate and promote cross-border competition.
Given the enormous material and ideal potential for damage caused by manipulation and corruption in the award of construction services, both Courts are calling on construction administrations in their countries to pursue their actions against corruption and manipulation and, if necessary, to improve them further. n.a.
In particular, the organisation and procedures of procurement procedures should be constantly examined to identify weaknesses and risks in order to identify the need for action and to take appropriate countermeasures.
The comparison of procurement practices in both countries suggests that the proportion of open procedures in the Czech Republic should be increased as open procedures offer a wider scope for competition and can significantly reduce the risk of corruption.
A greater division of construction services into lots may also have a favourable effect on supply prices, provided that this results in greater competition with a higher number of bidders.
Ensuring the correct implementation of procurement procedures is an essential basis for the efficient award of contracting authorities.
In Germany, the award procedures are carried out by the specialised construction administrations, while in the Czech Republic, with the exception of transport construction projects, these tasks are carried out by the services themselves or by contractors entrusted to them.
The auditors of both countries are concerned to continue developing the relevant knowledge for each of them, even after the completion of their joint project, and, where appropriate, to bring it to their national parliament and government.
Both Courts are also convinced that the principles of procurement law set out in this report and its implementation are also of interest at the international level of the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI), because the principles set out above are: insights and insights are of general importance to effectively combat corruption and to ensure the economic award of construction services in a well-functioning and fair competition.
